{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5294","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:50 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:50 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">Apart from the particle <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནས་</span>, Literary Tibetan also uses the marker <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་</span> to express spatial provenance. The difference between the two is so subtle as to be nonexistent in certain cases. At an abstract level, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་</span> may be said to signify a consubstantial origin whereas <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནས་</span> implies that an object and its source are ontologically different. Another way of expressing the difference would be to say that for <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནས་</span> the original space is closed or delimited, whereas for <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་</span> the space is conceived as open and unbounded.<a href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a></p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Concretely, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་</span> is used in principle to denote the material that something is made of, or consubstantial provenance, or the source of a quotation, whereas <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནས་</span> refers to spatial or temporal origin.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གསེར་ལས་བུམ་པ་བྱས་</span> “To make a vase out of gold” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཤིང་ལས་ཁང་པ་གྲུབ་</span> “To build a house out of wood” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དངུལ་ལས་རྡོ་རྗེ་གྲུབ་</span> “To make a <em>vajra </em>out of silver” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འོ་མ་ལས་མར་བླངས་</span> “To make butter from milk” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཉི་མ་ལས་འོད་འཕྲོས་</span> “Light emitted by the sun” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པད་མ་བཀའ་ཐང་ལས་</span> “According to the <em>Padma bka’ thang</em>” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རི་རྩེ་ནས་བབས་</span> “To come down from the mountain-top” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཤར་ཕྱོགས་ནས་འོང་</span> “Come from the east” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཟླ་བ་བཅུ་པ་ནས་འགོ་ཚུགས་</span> “Beginning in the tenth month” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགྲ་བོའི་ལག་ནས་ཤོར་</span> “Escaped from enemy hands”</li> </ul> <hr size=\"1\" /> <p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\">[1]</a> This is suggested in Stephan Beyer, <em>The Classical Tibetan Language</em> (Albany: State University of New York Press, 1992).</p>","title":""}]}
